    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w33895</id>
    <title>Measuring Industrial Policy: A Text-Based Approach</title>
    <updated>2025-06-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Réka Juhász, Nathan J. Lane, Emily Oehlsen &amp; Veronica C. Perez</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;Since the 18th century, policymakers have debated the merits of industrial policy (IP). Yet, economists lack basic facts about its use due to measurement challenges. We propose a new approach to IP measurement based on information contained in policy text. We show how off-the-shelf supervised machine learning tools can be used to categorize industrial policies at scale. Using this approach, we validate long-standing concerns with earlier measurement approaches that conflate IP with other types of policy. We apply our methodology to a global database of commercial policy descriptions, and provide a first look at IP use at the country, industry, and year levels (2010-2022). The new data on IP suggest that i) IP is on the rise; ii) modern IP tends to use subsidies and export promotion measures as opposed to tariffs; iii) rich countries heavily dominate IP use; iv) IP tends to target sectors with an established comparative advantage, particularly in high-income countries.</content>
    <link href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w33895"/>
    <category term="NBER"/>
    <published>2025-06-01T00:00:00+00:00</published>
