    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w33923</id>
    <title>Like Great-Grandparent, Like Great-Grandchild? Multigenerational Mobility in American History</title>
    <updated>2025-06-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Zachary Ward, Kasey Buckles &amp; Joseph Price</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;Using data on 2.5 million great-grandchildren linked to their great-grandfathers in the US (1850–1940), we show that economic gaps persisted strongly across four generations despite major structural change. We find that one-third of the initial differences in economic status across white great-grandfathers remained in their great-grandchildren. When including both Black and white families, this persistence rises to about 50 percent, largely because the gap between Black and white families closed slowly over time. Grandparent and great-grandparent status matter beyond the father's status, indicating slower convergence to the mean than predicted by two-generational estimates. However, this excess persistence is largely driven by enduring racial inequality as grandparent effects are small within the white population.</content>
    <link href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w33923"/>
    <category term="NBER"/>
    <published>2025-06-01T00:00:00+00:00</published>
